Text.Value: I already met her - she says Halsin left the grove with you. Is that true?
I'm drinkin'. You're leavin'.
Half my crew are full of holes.
Fair enough. I ain't tryin' to start the shite with you, anyway. Been a day.
What's a home for if not for sharing? Who lives here?
And whose home is this exactly?
Leave.
Them devils ain't local - they're refugees. Fella who runs this place offered 'em shelter.
We've got a contract to track down some relic, and he wanted in on the job. Eyes lit up when he heard about it.
You might be, if you demonstrated more honour in your dealings.
Wasn't no few goblins, mate. There's an entire hive of 'em. Contract failed to mention that part.
Yeah, and I'd do the same again. He weren't my responsibility.
Glad you weren't - you fight well. Not like them bloody tieflings.
Yeah? And how's that workin' out for you? Stuck in this hellhole with the rest of us.
Yeah, you really saved the day, swooping in and playing the hero.
You're outta luck. Halsin - druid who runs this place - knew his stuff. But he ain't here anymore.
They chased us all the way from the ruins we were poking around in.
I should speak with that fellow. Do you know where he is?
Sounds like you were looking for trouble.
Who's the druid you lost track of?
If you head that way, you'll likely smell 'em or hear their drums before you see 'em.
I heard the First Druid left the grove with you. Any truth in that?
As soon as he heard we had a contract to find that Nightsong relic, he was more eager than a hound in heat.
I need a stronger drink. And you need to get out of my face.
Doubt it.
Attack.
But look, if you're itching to meet Kelemvor, I won't stop you.
And is that where you lost track of the druid you mentioned?
I could use some help - is there a healer here?
Thanks.

EditorData.NodeContext: With acid. The player just called him a miserable old moaner, Aradin says 'thanks' with sarcasm and takes his leave.

Text.Value: Leave.
I'm not leaving until you tell me exactly what happened to the First Druid.
Drinking won't solve your problems. You need a plan.
No - I'm staying. You need to learn some manners.
You don't need company?
Not my concern. Is there a healer round these parts?
You might have an easier time here if you demonstrated more honour in your dealings.
Fine. Plenty more attractive faces around.
Where did the goblins come from?
Prayer will help more than any drink.
Job's all yours, if you got a death wish.
Please. A good sword will get you farther than honour any day.
Heh, don't thank me. I'll be well on my way to Baldur's Gate when you die.
Maybe I could drink with you? A toast to our survival.
I already told you - he was at the temple ruins with us. But it ain't like we forced him to go along.
And you just left him to die?
Fine. You're miserable company anyhow.
You got along with their leader?
After the help I gave you, it would be honourable for you to address me differently.
Aye. His name's Halsin, and if he's still alive, he'll be cursing the day he laid eyes on me.
If it ain't the friendly drow. Thought you were with the goblins when you showed up at the gate.
I saved your skin at the gate - least you can do is answer a simple question.
It's called the Nightsong. Supposed to be hidden under the temple where the goblins jumped us.
Leave.
Outta my face, foulblood.
Outta my face, runt.
Outta my face, lizard.
Outta my face, ugly.
Outta my face.
When the goblins jumped us, most of my crew scarpered, just like I taught 'em to. The old codger didn't.
Now I'm gonna take the blame for leading the goblins here, and losing track of the bloody druid.

EditorData.NodeContext: He knows these things are his fault, but he's sulking and petulant about it

Text.Value: Druids. And they ain't the friendly type. The only one of 'em worth a damn was the leader, and he ain't here anymore.
They like trees more than they like people.
I'd give you the map and wish you a happy funeral, but my mate Brian kept hold of it like his own todger. Goblins made short of the fat old chunk.
Leave.
I'm not local either - got a problem with that?
I'll leave when you tell me what happened to the First Druid.
Didn't work out, though. Goblins got him when we were turning tail. He's either diggin' latrines or boilin' in a cookpot by now.
Better than the others, but not well enough to risk my neck for him.
And where exactly did you leave him?
I'm more concerned about the First Druid - heard he left the grove with you?
Charming. I can see why the locals like you so much.
Just trying to get the lay of the land.
All right. I'll leave you to your drinking.
Just tell me where to find the relic.
Devils? Seriously? They're tieflings. Same as me.
What do you want, anyway? I ain't local. I know - knew - the fella in charge, but barely said two words to the devils swarming his place.
You should drink to celebrate victory, not to forget your defeats.
You got along with their leader, though?
Suit yourself.
Leave.
Show some respect - I helped at the gates.
Feck off yourself - I saved your skin back at the gates.
Yes - it's where I got my good looks. Did you come from a gelatinous ooze?
Thanks.
And from a wizard, too. I shoulda known. The gold probably turns to lead the moment you leave Baldur's Gate.
If you want to play the hero, go ask the goblins nicely, and maybe they'll give you whatever's left of him.
Do you have any idea where Halsin went?
Not the best place for drinking. How'd you end up here?
What's it to you?
If I knew that, I wouldn't be back here with half my crew gone.
I heard you might know where he is.
You fought well, too.
Think he's got an apprentice running around somewheres though. Nadine? Natalie? Something like that.
Didn't ask for your help. You can keep your honour and stick it somewhere else.
Can I have a look at that contract?
What makes you say they're not friendly?
All I've got's the contract. It'll show you where we turned back, if you feel like dying.
Halsin. He's the leader around these parts. Or was.
Gobbos are holed up in the temple ruins out west of here - last I saw Halsin, he was right in the thick of 'em.
If it ain't the fearless goblin-slayer.

EditorData.NodeContext: Aggressive, but not powerfully so. He's not a friendly guy.

Text.Value: How'd you end up here in the first place?
What? You lot come from devils, don't you?
Talking about your troubles might help.
I think they like you less than they like me. It's almost impressive, how detestable you are.
There's a wizard in Baldur's Gate that'll pay gobloads for a relic, supposedly buried round these parts.
I ain't toasting to nothing. Half my people are captured or dead.
You sure you want to be seen with me? I ain't exactly popular with this lot.

EditorData.NodeContext: with a grimace - 'this lot' refers specifically to the tiefling refugees who are nearby but not necessarily in-shot, but he's grumpy enough that it also refers to just about everybody in the world

Text.Value: You ran away from a few goblins?
Stupid thing to die for...
What are you doing round these parts?
Do you have any idea where he is?
All I need's a way out of this hellhole.
You were more fun when you were running from goblins.
First, I lost half my crew in some godforsaken temple.
Any idea what the relic actually is?
Did you think getting rich would be easy?
You could try to be a little friendlier.
Dunno what I expected. That much gold for some long-lost relic. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
Nothing to see here, mate.
We was looking for a relic. Had a contract to find it, and the fella who runs this place came along on the job with us.
All you did was stand up for your crew. I respect that.
What happened to their leader?
Bet I could find something nasty in your family tree, too.
Thanks, mum. Now please do feck off.
Oh, feck off.
But gold ain't any use if you're too cold to spend it.

Synopsis: Adventurer leader dialogue. Mostly used during Adventurers Quest. This is after the player has stopped Zevlor and Aradin from fighting one another. Aradin returns to his den to lick his wounds.
